docs\qa\assetswap-real-bundles-spec.md:1:# AssetSwap Real Bundles Spec
docs\qa\assetswap-real-bundles-spec.md:19:**The 90-byte stubs are the direct cause of the 0/36 rendering failure for building-type units.** They have the correct bundle name (e.g. `sw-guard-tower`) and appear in `AssetBundles.manifest`, but their `UnityFS` block carries zero asset data. `AssetBundle.LoadFromFile()` succeeds (the file is a valid but empty UnityFS), then every `LoadAsset<T>` call returns null, so `TrySwapRenderMeshFromBundle` returns false and no swap is applied.
docs\qa\assetswap-real-bundles-spec.md:71:### How AssetSwapSystem Loads the Bundle
docs\qa\assetswap-real-bundles-spec.md:73:`AssetSwapSystem.TrySwapRenderMeshFromBundle()` does:
docs\qa\assetswap-real-bundles-spec.md:81:**Critical**: `assetName` in the swap request must equal `GameObject.name` in the bundle. The existing `GenerateStarWarsPrefabs.cs` and `GenerateStarWarsPrefabsFromModels.cs` both set `go.name = def.BundleKey` — this is correct and matches the expected behavior.
docs\qa\assetswap-real-bundles-spec.md:164:**One narrow exception**: If a bundle was already built by Unity 2021.3 (e.g. the 44KB primitive bundles), AssetsTools.NET *could* in principle overwrite the Mesh bytes with new geometry in-place, since the type tree is already correct for this Unity version. This would be a "bundle patch" approach — copy a working primitive bundle and replace its mesh data. This is feasible for swapping geometry but is fragile (requires exact size matching or raw binary surgery) and would not give a clean solution. It is not recommended.
docs\qa\assetswap-real-bundles-spec.md:208:These work (AssetSwap can load and render them) but show Unity primitive geometry, not Star Wars models.
docs\qa\assetswap-real-bundles-spec.md:313:- The asset name convention (`go.name = bundleKey`) is correct for AssetSwapSystem's `LoadAsset<GameObject>(assetName)` fallback path
